contexts.text: I've noticed that most of the problems seem to occur when they assume I am a new user (the random ones you get for hitting help help) and asking a way more basic question than what I was actually asking.

From the FAQ I think it is fairly clear that it is OK: Can I open a Help to Buy: ISA with someone else? No. Help to Buy:   ISAs are only available to individuals. But, you can put more than one   government bonus towards the home you are buying. So, if you are   buying a home with someone else who is also a first time buyer, they   can open and save money into their own account and receive a   government bonus. Inference: if you are buying a home with someone else who is NOT also a first time buyer, they can't get their own account and get the bonus (but there's no problem with you doing so).  Alternatively - open the Help To Buy ISA, you'll still get the normal interest rate on it, and then argue the case with the conveyancer / solicitor once you actually buy the property and claim the Government bonus. In fact, here is the declaration you (well, specifically, your girlfriend) would have to sign at the point you jointly make the purchase. Nothing in there that forbids it being a joint purchase with a non-first-time-buyer either.

I remember walking into Sears with every intention of buying an expensive TV.  I waited for 15 minutes for an employee to notice me and come help.  Nothin'.  I kept catching their eye and giving the eyebrows-raised, hey-can-you-help-me smile.  Nothin'.  I ended up walking out and going to London Drugs, of all places, where the staff was super helpful.

messages.original_text:
Sure, I'd be happy to explain the difference between debit and credit cards. 
A debit card takes the funds directly from your account when you make a purchase. There's no loan or credit involved, it's just your money being spent.
On the other hand, a credit card facilitates a short term loan. When you make a purchase with a credit card, you're essentially borrowing money from the bank, which you then pay back later. This loan comes with interest charges, unless you pay your balance in full each month.
Additionally, as mentioned in the documents, there can be differences in how merchants handle debit and credit cards, and there can be advantages to having both types of cards for backup in case of issues with the other.

messages.original_text:
I understand that choosing a credit card can be overwhelming due to the variety of options available. Here are some tips that might help you:
1. Look for a card that gives you the best rewards without charging you an annual or other fees. Since you're planning to pay off the full balance by the due date, you won't have to worry about the interest rate. Just ensure you get an interest-free period.
2. Make sure the card delivers on the benefits you expect. Avoid selecting a card with an annual fee. Cash is generally better than miles for most people. Also, ensure that the best earnings aren't only from shopping at one gas station or one store. The maximum cash back might be only for a limited time or only after you've charged thousands of dollars that year.
3. Using a credit card can positively impact your credit rating. It also minimizes the chances of accidentally overdrawing the linked account, as there's only one big scheduled withdrawal a month instead of dozens of unscheduled ones.
Remember, the best credit card for you depends on your personal spending habits and financial goals. It's always a good idea to compare different cards and read the terms and conditions carefully before making a decision.
